					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Oh, and the missing dot...<br />I've read this somewhere else aleady, but here's it again, confirmed by my test proggy: There is missing dot on PAL consoles. And on NTSC consoles it does actually miss only if BG layer is enabled (does NOT miss if BG and OBJ layers are both off) (haven't tested what happens when only OBJ layer is on).<br /><br />According to the <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Clock_rate">http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Clock_rate</a><!-- m -->, the missing dot is located in the &quot;pre-render&quot; (aka &quot;post-blank&quot;) scanline. How was that confirmed, and is it really true? Asking because it'd be a BAD location. From my experiences, analog CRT TVs do need some time to &quot;settle&quot; on the HSYNC rate. For example, if you display a vertical line, and then add/remove one dot, then the vertical line will look somehow curved in next 10-15 scanlines.<br /><br />If the missing dot occurs right before the picture rendering period, then the topmost scanlines of the picture should look somehow distorted. Instead of a vertical line you would get the curved-line effect in each 2nd frame, and a normal vertical line in each other frame (which together may look like a flimmering bold line). Is there any such effect on NTSC NES consoles?<br />Of course, 224 lines NTSC TVs will clip the upper ~8 lines, so that would also &quot;hide&quot; dirt effects in that lines.<br /><br />For reference:<br />The NTSC SNES is having it's missing dot in the post-rendering line (which means no dirt).<br />The PAL SNES in interlace mode is having a long scanline located at end of vblank (which does actually produce that curvy-line dirt effect)).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

