						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">nocash wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">And on NTSC consoles it does actually miss only if BG layer is enabled (does NOT miss if BG and OBJ layers are both off) (haven't tested what happens when only OBJ layer is on).</div><br />If one layer is on but the other is off, the PPU still does all tasks related to the rendering of both layers, it just doesn't show the one that's off. So the dot is indeed skipped even when only sprites are on (I tested this personally even, when I was studying the best way to turn rendering on late in order to transfer more stuff to VRAM).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Is there any such effect on NTSC NES consoles?</div><br />I don't know exactly what a &quot;curved line&quot; would look like, but the missing dot does affect how colors are rendered. Someone will explain you how exactly this works because I don't understand the technical details myself, but in practice, that missing dot is there to modify the dot crawl you get in NTSC. You can see the difference in Blargg's NTSC filter, present in Nestopia for example. Games that turn rendering on late (Battletoads is an example) don't have this dot skipped, so the dot crawl looks very different.</div>

