			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I never noticed anything like that... but the only time I can see the complete image is through my capture card... would the effect be visible that way or just with an actual TV?</div><br />May vary from hardware to hardware. Analog CRTs are probably more likely to produce that effects. Digital video grabbers might immediately adopt themselves to changed HSYNC timings - or maybe they do compute the average HBLANK time across several scanlines (to eliminate dirty signals) - then they would show the effect, too.<br /><br />As far as I understood, the current proof for the missing dot location is that it depends on BG/OBJ enable bits at vblank end. But then it might be also possible that the hardware toggles an even/odd frame flag in that place, and then waits till vblank start, and removes the dot in that place.<br /><br />Best way to see the missing dot location would be viewing it with a good oscilloscope. Best by strobing the 4016h.W signal (as trigger point) shortly before Vblank start, and, in another test, shortly before Vblank end. Somewhere at that locations one should see a slightly shorter scanline. Or if it's a very good oscilloscope, then one could simply use /NMI or VSYNC as trigger points and scroll the picture left/right towards the vblank start/end locations.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

